Here's what I read, with a little bit of my ideas thrown in too. While in the game, Guy meets a new NPC A.I. named Gal (name meaning girl; opposite of guy). I figured it would be a nice joke. We will see them go on a date together, not just with eating bubblegum ice cream or going on the swings, but also riding on unicorns since that was mentioned at the end of the movie with how the game's been updated. Later on, we find out that Gal was created by Antwan (or a different villain) to get information and shut everything down. Gal will of course fight Guy for a little bit and of course, he'll get upset for being played. Millie will comfort him saying he didn't deserve to be treated like that and he will find someone. Guy then flips out saying that there is no other NPC in the game interested in him. That only NPC girls in the game want to be his friend and nothing more. Later, they talk about how they need to take down the villain. It then comes to the point when Guy, Millie's avatar, Keys' avatar, Mouser's avatar, Buddy, and Dude need to break into a headquarters of the villain in the game to retrieve their stolen information. While there, Dude could meet a way bigger version of himself called "Bro". Mouser or Buddy would then say "Oh this is bad." A muscular version of Buddy could appear named "Pal". Buddy could meet a lady security guard who tries to stop him, but they quickly begin to connect. Gal feels terrible for what she did and realizes that Guy really is a great person for her. With this, she tries to redeem herself to help. Gal nearly gets shutdown in the end for her betrayal, but she will be all right in the end. Keys builds a great wedding for Guy and Gal and there, Buddy is the best man. Keys tells Buddy he will do the best he can to construct the best honeymoon for them possible. Comment:
This movie is PERFECT in its take on video games and the video gaming industry. Literally almost everything in it is based on a real incident. Everything from the sociopathic content-thieving CEO
to the obsession with mindless violence through the hellishly repetitive coding of the NPC player's existence. Even the main character's moniker "blue shirt guy" is a clever reference to the way gamers fetishize unremarkable objects in a video game because of their exclusivity. My favourite bit was the final boss-type character at the end "dude" yelling "catchphrase" at the hero before attacking him because the makers hadn't finished coding him properly. Even the stuff about AI isn't that far fetched now (in fact weirdly prophetic-NPC's were only given intelligence in games like this in the last few years).
If you aren't interested in video games and the video game industry it is just a mildly enjoyable very silly film that will keep you entertained but you will instantly forgettable.I have to say though it is incredibly satisfying to see a mainstream film cover gaming, or indeed anything, this accurately.
